\begin_layout Section
Elementary notions of conditional probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic notion of conditional probabilities is clear when we are conditioning
 of events of positive probability.
 That is, on a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\probabilityspace$
\end_inset

 with an event 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(B\right)>0$
\end_inset

, we can easily define a conditional measure
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\P_{B}\left(A\right):=\frac{\P\left(A\cap B\right)}{\P\left(B\right)}\label{eq:conditionalProbabilityPositive}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sometimes we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(A\mid B\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\P_{B}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 if the event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is actually some long expression like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X=1\right\} ".$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\P_{B}$
\end_inset

 is in fact a probability measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\F$
\end_inset

 and thus we can derive the corresponding integral 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E_{B}\left[f\right]=\frac{\E\left[f\indicate_{B}\right]}{\P\left(B\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

This definition quickly yields some of the most foundational and basic probabili
stic ideas: for instance with two events 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 where both occur with positive probability, they are independent if and
 only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(A\right)=\P_{B}\left(A\right).$
\end_inset

The following basic facts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:totalProbability"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\probabilityspace$
\end_inset

 be a probability space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\F$
\end_inset

 be an event.
 Then for any countable partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(A_{i}\right)>0$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\P\left(B\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\P\left(A_{i}\right)\P_{A_{i}}\left(B\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that by countable additivity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\P\left(B\right) & =\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\P\left(B\cap A_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\P\left(A_{i}\right)\P_{A_{i}}\left(B\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This immediately yields the famous Bayes Theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:bayesTheorem"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\probabilityspace$
\end_inset

 be a probability space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

be a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(A_{i}\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\F$
\end_inset

 with positive probability,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\P_{B}\left(A\right)=\frac{\P_{A}\left(B\right)\P\left(A\right)}{\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\P\left(A_{i}\right)\P_{A_{i}}\left(B\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

